                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Grrrr!
<br />

<br />
In my circle of friends, not one of them has ever gotten an enchanter past level 10 or so.  As a result, none of them really understands what I can and can't do.
<br />

<br />
So we're experimenting in Halls of Honor, trying out charm--I've always been leery of charm, but lately I'm trying to stretch my repertoire.  We're just dinking around--I've charmed one of the itty bitty wrulons at the zone in and am sending it in with with our pally tank.  Wizard says, "Boy, it'll be great when you get Dire Charm and can use it on these guards."  Hello?  If you could Dire Charm stuff up to 60 or so, enchanters would never group with anybody.
<br />

<br />
Then, I notice that whenever my charm breaks, my friend points it out with this sort of tone like, "What's wrong with you?  Your pet is broken!"  I can't figure out why until he says, "So, when if your charm due to break?"  So I'm all like, "How the heck should I know?" and he's all like, "It isn't a set duration?"  Well, geez, no wonder he kind of has been hinting I'm a wuss for not charming, if he thinks I can know exactly when it's going to break!  And what a moron he must have thought I was when I didn't get it under control immediately.
<br />

<br />
I mean, I'm as guilty as they are in reverse with their classes--I just posted a bunch of clueless questions about wizards in the ooc board.  And I just found out recently that necros could mez.    <img src="images/smiles/icon_redface.gif" alt="icon_redface.gif" border="0" />  But sometimes I do wish they would try playing an enchanter so they would at least not assume the hard things were easy!</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://home.att.ne.jp/apple/dmolden/screenshots/pixcol.gif" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=611032" target="_blank" class="postlink">Columbyne Celebfin</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
