                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Get comfortable with charming before you haste a level 60 plus pet with CoD.  As others alluded to, having a druid or ranger snare a hasted pet will often prevent you (or other group members) from being "1-rounded" when charm breaks.
<br />

<br />
The large wrulon (cats) can also be charmed, but the humans in HoH seem to be the best pets.
<br />

<br />
If you go to BoT, try charming a <insert giant name> Tyv.  Jord Tyv's and the other Tyv's are straight melee mobs (no downtime casting on targets or self-buffing) and, while they will summon if damaged more than 98 pct, have very low MR.
<br />

<br />
It's been covered in other posts, but always tash your pet - and if a Shaman or Mage is present have them cast the longest-lasting version of the Malo line to debuff MR further.  Lowering the MR of the pet makes your charm last much longer.
<br />

<br />
You've also probably noticed when slowing that some individual mobs have higher innate MR - taking multiple casts to slow, mez, etc.  If you are getting really fast charm breaks on one pet, don't be discouraged.  Mez it, debuff it, kill it and find another pet.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="color: darkblue"> 
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=831098" target="_blank" class="postlink">Sage Nokei Orhaste</a></span>
<br />
Coercer for <span style="color: blue"><a href="http://www.houseofaegis.com" target="_blank" class="postlink">House of Aegis</a></span>
<br />
Luclin
<br />

<br />
E65.170/L h++ 2.7khp 4.4km ft11
